# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: istio-mesh
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:istio-mesh/architecture] An Istio service mesh is logically split into a **data plane** and a **control plane**.
[src:istio-mesh/architecture] The following sections provide a brief overview of each of Istio’s core components.
[src:istio-mesh/architecture] Istio uses an extended version of the Envoy proxy.
[src:istio-mesh/architecture] Envoy is a high-performance proxy developed in C++ to mediate all inbound and outbound traffic for all services in the service mesh.
[src:istio-mesh/architecture] Envoy proxies are the only Istio components that interact with data plane traffic.
[src:istio-mesh/architecture] This sidecar deployment allows Istio to enforce policy decisions and extract rich telemetry which can be sent to monitoring systems to provide information about the behavior of the entire mesh.
[src:istio-mesh/architecture] The sidecar proxy model also allows you to add Istio capabilities to an existing deployment without requiring you to rearchitect or rewrite code.
[src:istio-mesh/architecture] Istiod provides service discovery, configuration and certificate management.
[src:istio-mesh/architecture] Istiod converts high level routing rules that control traffic behavior into Envoy-specific configurations, and propagates them to the sidecars at runtime.
[src:istio-mesh/architecture] It abstracts platform-specific service discovery mechanisms and synthesizes them into a standard format that any sidecar conforming with the Envoy API can consume.
[src:istio-mesh/architecture] Istio can support discovery for multiple environments such as Kubernetes or VMs.
[src:istio-mesh/architecture] You can use Istio’s Traffic Management API to instruct Istiod to refine the Envoy configuration to exercise more granular control over the traffic in your service mesh.
[src:istio-mesh/architecture] Istiod security enables strong service-to-service and end-user authentication with built-in identity and credential management.
[src:istio-mesh/architecture] You can use Istio to upgrade unencrypted traffic in the service mesh.
[src:istio-mesh/architecture] Using Istio, operators can enforce policies based on service identity rather than on relatively unstable layer 3 or layer 4 network identifiers.
[src:istio-mesh/architecture] Additionally, you can use Istio’s authorization feature to control who can access your services.
[src:istio-mesh/architecture] Istiod acts as a Certificate Authority (CA) and generates certificates to allow secure mTLS communication in the data plane.
[src:istio-mesh/cloud-native-computing-foundation] The **Cloud Native Computing Foundation** (**CNCF**) is a subsidiary of the Linux Foundation founded in 2015 to support cloud-native computing.
[src:istio-mesh/cloud-native-computing-foundation] It was announced alongside Kubernetes 1.0, an open source container cluster manager, which was contributed to the Linux Foundation by Google as a seed technology.
[src:istio-mesh/cloud-native-computing-foundation] Founding members include Google, CoreOS, Mesosphere, Red Hat, Twitter, Huawei, Intel, RX-M, Cisco, IBM, Docker, Univa, and VMware.
[src:istio-mesh/cloud-native-computing-foundation] Today, CNCF is supported by over 450 members.
[src:istio-mesh/cloud-native-computing-foundation] In August 2018 Google announced that it was handing over operational control of Kubernetes to the community.
[src:istio-mesh/latest] Learn how to deploy, use, and operate Istio.
[src:istio-mesh/latest] A high-level introduction to Istio and service mesh.
[src:istio-mesh/latest] Learn about the different parts of the Istio system and the abstractions it uses.
[src:istio-mesh/latest] Information for setting up and operating Istio in sidecar mode.
[src:istio-mesh/latest] Information for setting up and operating Istio with support for ambient mode.
[src:istio-mesh/latest] How to do single specific targeted activities with the Istio system.
[src:istio-mesh/latest] A variety of fully working example uses for Istio that you can experiment with.
[src:istio-mesh/latest] Concepts, tools, and techniques to deploy and manage an Istio mesh.
[src:istio-mesh/latest] Detailed authoritative reference material such as command-line options, configuration options, and API calling parameters.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] In software engineering, a **microservice** architecture is an architectural pattern that organizes an application into a collection of loosely coupled, fine-grained services that communicate through lightweight protocols.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] This pattern allows teams to develop, deploy, and scale services independently, improving modularity, scalability, and adaptability.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] However, it introduces additional complexity, particularly in managing distributed systems and inter-service communication, making the initial implementation more challenging compared to a monolithic architecture.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] There is no single, universally agreed-upon definition of microservices.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] However, they are generally characterized by a focus on modularity, with each service designed around a specific business capability.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] These services are loosely coupled, independently deployable, and often developed and scaled separately, enabling greater flexibility and agility in managing complex systems.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Microservices architecture is closely associated with principles such as domain-driven design, decentralization of data and governance, and the flexibility to use different technologies for individual services to best meet their requirements.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] It is common for microservices architectures to be adopted for cloud-native applications, serverless computing, and applications using lightweight container deployment via OS-level virtualization.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] According to Fowler, because of the large number (when compared to monolithic application implementations) of services, decentralized continuous delivery and DevOps with holistic service monitoring are necessary to effectively develop, maintain, and operate such applications.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] A consequence of (and rationale for) following this approach is that the individual microservices can be individually scaled.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] In the monolithic approach, an application supporting three functions would have to be scaled in its entirety even if only one of these functions had a resource constraint.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] With microservices, only the microservice supporting the function with resource constraints needs to be scaled out, thus providing resource and cost optimization benefits.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Despite its benefits, microservices architecture introduces challenges such as increased operational complexity, network latency, and the need for robust monitoring and fault tolerance mechanisms.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing design in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Each cell operates independently, handling a subset of requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] A cell typically consists of multiple microservices and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] In some implementations, entire sets of microservices are replicated across multiple cells, enabling requests to be rerouted to another operational cell if one experiences a failure.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] This approach is intended to improve system-wide resilience by limiting the impact of localized failures.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Some implementations incorporate circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to mitigate cascading failures among microservices, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in certain large-scale distributed systems where fault isolation and redundancy are design priorities.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Its implementation varies based on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and specific operational goals.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] In 1999, software developer Peter Rodgers had been working on the Dexter research project at Hewlett Packard Labs, whose aim was to make code less brittle and to make large-scale, complex software systems robust to change.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Ultimately this path of research led to the development of resource-oriented computing (ROC), a generalized computation abstraction in which REST is a special subset.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] In 2005, during a presentation at the Web Services Edge conference, Rodgers argued for "REST-services" and stated that "Software components are Micro-Web-Services...
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Micro-Services are composed using Unix-like pipelines (the Web meets Unix = true loose-coupling).
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Services can call services (+multiple language run-times).
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Complex service assemblies are abstracted behind simple URI interfaces.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Also in 2005, Alistair Cockburn wrote about hexagonal architecture which is a software design pattern that is used along with the microservices.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] This pattern makes the design of the microservice possible since it isolates in layers the business logic from the auxiliary services needed in order to deploy and run the microservice completely independent from others.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Determining the appropriate level of (micro)service granularity in a microservices architecture often requires iterative collaboration between architects and developers.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] This process involves evaluating user requirements, service responsibilities, and architectural characteristics, such as non-functional requirements.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Neal Ford highlights the role of integrator and disintegrator factors in this context.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Integrator factors, such as shared transactions or tightly coupled processes, favor combining services, while disintegrator factors, such as fault tolerance or independent scalability, encourage splitting services to meet operational and architectural goals.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Additionally, fitness functions, as proposed by Neal Ford, can be used to validate architectural decisions and service granularity by continuously measuring system qualities or behaviors that are critical to stakeholders, ensuring alignment with overall architectural objectives.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] In microservices architectures, service granularity influences testing, deployment, performance, and reliability.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Very fine-grained microservices are typically easier to test and deploy independently, but they often experience lower performance and reduced overall reliability due to increased interservice communication and more complex service choreography.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Coarse-grained services exhibit contrasting characteristics.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] They generally provide higher robustness and reliability by minimizing communication overhead and coordination complexity, but they are more challenging to test and deploy because modifications affect a broader functional scope.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] The appropriate level of service granularity is determined by business drivers.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Architectural decisions commonly begin with identifying these drivers and then aligning architectural characteristics such as performance, scalability, reliability, or deployment flexibility to support them.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] A bounded context, a fundamental concept in domain-driven design (DDD), defines a specific area within which a domain model is consistent and valid, ensuring clarity and separation of concerns.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] In microservices architecture, a bounded context often maps to a microservice, but this relationship can vary depending on the design approach.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] A one-to-one relationship, where each bounded context is implemented as a single microservice, is typically ideal as it maintains clear boundaries, reduces coupling, and enables independent deployment and scaling.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] The choice of relationship should balance the principles of DDD with the system's business goals, technical constraints, and operational requirements.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] The architecture introduces additional complexity and new problems to deal with, such as latency, message format design, backup/availability/consistency (BAC), load balancing and fault tolerance.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] All of these problems have to be addressed at scale.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] The complexity of a monolithic application does not disappear if it is re-implemented as a set of microservices.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Some of the complexity gets translated into operational complexity.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Other places where the complexity manifests itself are increased network traffic and slower performance.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Also, an application made up of any number of microservices has a larger number of interface points to access its respective ecosystem, which increases the architectural complexity.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Various organizing principles (such as hypermedia as the engine of application state (HATEOAS), interface and data model documentation captured via Swagger, etc.) have been applied to reduce the impact of such additional complexity.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Microservices are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing – a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Ideally, microservices follow a "share-nothing" architecture.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] However, in practice, microservices architectures often encounter situations where code must be shared across services.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Each approach has its advantages and trade-offs, depending on the specific context and requirements.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Richards & Ford in *Fundamentals of software architecture* (2020) propose each microservice should have its own architectural characteristics (a.k.a. non functional requirements), and architects should not define uniform characteristics for the entire distributed system.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] To avoid having to coordinate deployments across different microservices, Sam Newman suggests keeping the interfaces of microservices stable and making backwards-compatible changes as interfaces evolve.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] On the topic of testing, Newman in *Building Microservices* (2015) proposes consumer-driven contract testing as a better alternative to traditional end-to-end testing in the context of microservices.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] He also suggests the use of log aggregation and metrics aggregation as well as distributed tracing tools to ensure the observability of systems composed of microservices.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Computer microservices can be implemented in different programming languages and might use different infrastructures.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Therefore, the most important technology choices are the way microservices communicate with each other (synchronous, asynchronous, UI integration) and the protocols used for the communication (e.g.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] In a traditional system, most technology choices like the programming language impact the whole system.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] Therefore, the approach to choosing technologies is quite different.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] The Eclipse Foundation has published a specification for developing microservices, Eclipse MicroProfile.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] In a service mesh, each service instance is paired with an instance of a reverse proxy server, called a service proxy, sidecar proxy, or sidecar.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] The service instance and sidecar proxy share a container, and the containers are managed by a container orchestration tool such as Kubernetes, Docker Swarm, or DC/OS.
[src:istio-mesh/microservices] The service proxies are responsible for communication with other service instances and can support capabilities such as service (instance) discovery, load balancing, authentication and authorization, secure communications, and others.
[src:istio-mesh/service-mesh] In software architecture, a **service mesh** is a dedicated infrastructure layer for facilitating service-to-service communications between services or microservices using a proxy.
[src:istio-mesh/service-mesh] A dedicated communication layer can provide numerous benefits, such as providing observability into communications, providing secure connections, and automating retries and backoff for failed requests.
[src:istio-mesh/service-mesh] A service mesh consists of network proxies paired with each service in an application and a set of task-management processes.
[src:istio-mesh/service-mesh] The proxies are called the data plane and the management processes are called the control plane.
[src:istio-mesh/service-mesh] The data plane intercepts calls between different services and processes them; the control plane is the brain of the mesh that coordinates the behavior of proxies and provides APIs for operations and maintenance personnel to manipulate and observe the entire network.
[src:istio-mesh/service-mesh] The service mesh architecture is implemented by software products such as Istio, Cilium, Linkerd, Consul, AWS App Mesh, Kuma, Traefik Mesh, and Greymatter.io.
[src:istio-mesh/service-mesh] Many service meshes use the Envoy proxy on the data plane.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Istio’s traffic routing rules let you easily control the flow of traffic and API calls between services.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Istio simplifies configuration of service-level properties like circuit breakers, timeouts, and retries, and makes it easy to set up important tasks like A/B testing, canary rollouts, and staged rollouts with percentage-based traffic splits.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] It also provides out-of-box reliability features that help make your application more resilient against failures of dependent services or the network.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Istio’s traffic management model relies on the Envoy proxies that are deployed along with your services.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] All traffic that your mesh services send and receive (data plane traffic) is proxied through Envoy, making it easy to direct and control traffic around your mesh without making any changes to your services.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] If you’re interested in the details of how the features described in this guide work, you can find out more about Istio’s traffic management implementation in the architecture overview.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] The rest of this guide introduces Istio’s traffic management features.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] In order to direct traffic within your mesh, Istio needs to know where all your endpoints are, and which services they belong to.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] To populate its own service registry, Istio connects to a service discovery system.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] For example, if you’ve installed Istio on a Kubernetes cluster, then Istio automatically detects the services and endpoints in that cluster.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Using this service registry, the Envoy proxies can then direct traffic to the relevant services.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Most microservice-based applications have multiple instances of each service workload to handle service traffic, sometimes referred to as a load balancing pool.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] While Istio’s basic service discovery and load balancing gives you a working service mesh, it’s far from all that Istio can do.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] In many cases you might want more fine-grained control over what happens to your mesh traffic.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You might want to direct a particular percentage of traffic to a new version of a service as part of A/B testing, or apply a different load balancing policy to traffic for a particular subset of service instances.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You might also want to apply special rules to traffic coming into or out of your mesh, or add an external dependency of your mesh to the service registry.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You can do all this and more by adding your own traffic configuration to Istio using Istio’s traffic management API.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Like other Istio configuration, the API is specified using Kubernetes custom resource definitions (CRDs), which you can configure using YAML, as you’ll see in the examples.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] The rest of this guide examines each of the traffic management API resources and what you can do with them.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] This guide also gives an overview of some of the network resilience and testing features that are built in to the API resources.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Virtual services, along with destination rules, are the key building blocks of Istio’s traffic routing functionality.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] A virtual service lets you configure how requests are routed to a service within an Istio service mesh, building on the basic connectivity and discovery provided by Istio and your platform.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Each virtual service consists of a set of routing rules that are evaluated in order, letting Istio match each given request to the virtual service to a specific real destination within the mesh.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Your mesh can require multiple virtual services or none depending on your use case.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Virtual services play a key role in making Istio’s traffic management flexible and powerful.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] They do this by strongly decoupling where clients send their requests from the destination workloads that actually implement them.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Virtual services also provide a rich way of specifying different traffic routing rules for sending traffic to those workloads.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Without virtual services, Envoy distributes traffic using least requests load balancing between all service instances, as described in the introduction.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You can improve this behavior with what you know about the workloads.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] For example, some might represent a different version.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] This can be useful in A/B testing, where you might want to configure traffic routes based on percentages across different service versions, or to direct traffic from your internal users to a particular set of instances.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] With a virtual service, you can specify traffic behavior for one or more hostnames.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You use routing rules in the virtual service that tell Envoy how to send the virtual service’s traffic to appropriate destinations.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Route destinations can be different versions of the same service or entirely different services.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] A typical use case is to send traffic to different versions of a service, specified as service subsets.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Clients send requests to the virtual service host as if it was a single entity, and Envoy then routes the traffic to the different versions depending on the virtual service rules: for example, “20% of calls go to the new version” or “calls from these users go to version 2”.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] This allows you to, for instance, create a canary rollout where you gradually increase the percentage of traffic that’s sent to a new service version.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] The traffic routing is completely separate from the instance deployment, meaning that the number of instances implementing the new service version can scale up and down based on traffic load without referring to traffic routing at all.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] By contrast, container orchestration platforms like Kubernetes only support traffic distribution based on instance scaling, which quickly becomes complex.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You can read more about how virtual services help with canary deployments in Canary Deployments using Istio.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] In some cases you also need to configure destination rules to use these features, as these are where you specify your service subsets.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Specifying service subsets and other destination-specific policies in a separate object lets you reuse these cleanly between virtual services.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You can find out more about destination rules in the next section.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] The following virtual service routes requests to different versions of a service depending on whether the request comes from a particular user.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] The `hosts` field lists the virtual service’s hosts - in other words, the user-addressable destination or destinations that these routing rules apply to.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] This is the address or addresses the client uses when sending requests to the service.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] The virtual service hostname can be an IP address, a DNS name, or, depending on the platform, a short name (such as a Kubernetes service short name) that resolves, implicitly or explicitly, to a fully qualified domain name (FQDN).
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You can also use wildcard ("*") prefixes, letting you create a single set of routing rules for all matching services.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Virtual service hosts don’t actually have to be part of the Istio service registry, they are simply virtual destinations.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] This lets you model traffic for virtual hosts that don’t have routable entries inside the mesh.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] A routing rule consists of the destination where you want the traffic to go and zero or more match conditions, depending on your use case.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] The first routing rule in the example has a condition and so begins with the `match` field.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] In this case you want this routing to apply to all requests from the user “jason”, so you use the `headers`, `end-user`, and `exact` fields to select the appropriate requests.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] The route section’s `destination` field specifies the actual destination for traffic that matches this condition.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Unlike the virtual service’s host(s), the destination’s host must be a real destination that exists in Istio’s service registry or Envoy won’t know where to send traffic to it.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] This can be a mesh service with proxies or a non-mesh service added using a service entry.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Note in this and the other examples on this page, we use a Kubernetes short name for the destination hosts for simplicity.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] When this rule is evaluated, Istio adds a domain suffix based on the namespace of the virtual service that contains the routing rule to get the fully qualified name for the host.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Using short names in our examples also means that you can copy and try them in any namespace you like.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] The destination section also specifies which subset of this Kubernetes service you want requests that match this rule’s conditions to go to, in this case the subset named v2.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You’ll see how you define a service subset in the section on destination rules below.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Routing rules are **evaluated in sequential order from top to bottom**, with the first rule in the virtual service definition being given highest priority.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] In this case you want anything that doesn’t match the first routing rule to go to a default destination, specified in the second rule.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Because of this, the second rule has no match conditions and just directs traffic to the v3 subset.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] We recommend providing a default “no condition” or weight-based rule (described below) like this as the last rule in each virtual service to ensure that traffic to the virtual service always has at least one matching route.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] As you saw above, routing rules are a powerful tool for routing particular subsets of traffic to particular destinations.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You can set match conditions on traffic ports, header fields, URIs, and more.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] For example, this virtual service lets users send traffic to two separate services, ratings and reviews, as if they were part of a bigger virtual service at `http://bookinfo.com/.` The virtual service rules match traffic based on request URIs and direct requests to the appropriate service.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] For some match conditions, you can also choose to select them using the exact value, a prefix, or a regex.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You can add multiple match conditions to the same `match` block to AND your conditions, or add multiple match blocks to the same rule to OR your conditions.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You can also have multiple routing rules for any given virtual service.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] This lets you make your routing conditions as complex or simple as you like within a single virtual service.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] A full list of match condition fields and their possible values can be found in the `HTTPMatchRequest` reference.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] In addition to using match conditions, you can distribute traffic by percentage “weight”.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] To learn more about the actions available, see the `HTTPRoute` reference.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Along with virtual services, destination rules are a key part of Istio’s traffic routing functionality.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You can think of virtual services as how you route your traffic **to** a given destination, and then you use destination rules to configure what happens to traffic **for** that destination.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Destination rules are applied after virtual service routing rules are evaluated, so they apply to the traffic’s “real” destination.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] In particular, you use destination rules to specify named service subsets, such as grouping all a given service’s instances by version.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You can then use these service subsets in the routing rules of virtual services to control the traffic to different instances of your services.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Destination rules also let you customize Envoy’s traffic policies when calling the entire destination service or a particular service subset, such as your preferred load balancing model, TLS security mode, or circuit breaker settings.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You can see a complete list of destination rule options in the Destination Rule reference.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] By default, Istio uses a least requests load balancing policy, where requests are distributed among the instances with the least number of requests.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Istio also supports the following models, which you can specify in destination rules for requests to a particular service or service subset.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] See the Envoy load balancing documentation for more information about each option.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Each subset is defined based on one or more `labels`, which in Kubernetes are key/value pairs that are attached to objects such as Pods.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] These labels are applied in the Kubernetes service’s deployment as `metadata` to identify different versions.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] As well as defining subsets, this destination rule has both a default traffic policy for all subsets in this destination and a subset-specific policy that overrides it for just that subset.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] The default policy, defined above the `subsets` field, sets a simple random load balancer for the `v1` and `v3` subsets.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] In the `v2` policy, a round-robin load balancer is specified in the corresponding subset’s field.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You use a gateway to manage inbound and outbound traffic for your mesh, letting you specify which traffic you want to enter or leave the mesh.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Gateway configurations are applied to standalone Envoy proxies that are running at the edge of the mesh, rather than sidecar Envoy proxies running alongside your service workloads.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Unlike other mechanisms for controlling traffic entering your systems, such as the Kubernetes Ingress APIs, Istio gateways let you use the full power and flexibility of Istio’s traffic routing.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You can do this because Istio’s Gateway resource just lets you configure layer 4-6 load balancing properties such as ports to expose, TLS settings, and so on.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Then instead of adding application-layer traffic routing (L7) to the same API resource, you bind a regular Istio virtual service to the gateway.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] This lets you basically manage gateway traffic like any other data plane traffic in an Istio mesh.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Gateways are primarily used to manage ingress traffic, but you can also configure egress gateways.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] An egress gateway lets you configure a dedicated exit node for the traffic leaving the mesh, letting you limit which services can or should access external networks, or to enable secure control of egress traffic to add security to your mesh, for example.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You can also use a gateway to configure a purely internal proxy.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Istio provides some preconfigured gateway proxy deployments (`istio-ingressgateway` and `istio-egressgateway`) that you can use - both are deployed if you use our demo installation, while just the ingress gateway is deployed with our default profile.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You can apply your own gateway configurations to these deployments or deploy and configure your own gateway proxies.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] This gateway configuration lets HTTPS traffic from `ext-host.example.com` into the mesh on port 443, but doesn’t specify any routing for the traffic.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] To specify routing and for the gateway to work as intended, you must also bind the gateway to a virtual service.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You can then configure the virtual service with routing rules for the external traffic.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You use a service entry to add an entry to the service registry that Istio maintains internally.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] After you add the service entry, the Envoy proxies can send traffic to the service as if it was a service in your mesh.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You don’t need to add a service entry for every external service that you want your mesh services to use.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] By default, Istio configures the Envoy proxies to passthrough requests to unknown services.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] However, you can’t use Istio features to control the traffic to destinations that aren’t registered in the mesh.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You specify the external resource using the `hosts` field.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You can qualify it fully or use a wildcard prefixed domain name.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You can configure virtual services and destination rules to control traffic to a service entry in a more granular way, in the same way you configure traffic for any other service in the mesh.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] See the Service Entry reference for more possible configuration options.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] By default, Istio configures every Envoy proxy to accept traffic on all the ports of its associated workload, and to reach every workload in the mesh when forwarding traffic.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You might want to limit sidecar reachability like this in larger applications, where having every proxy configured to reach every other service in the mesh can potentially affect mesh performance due to high memory usage.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You can specify that you want a sidecar configuration to apply to all workloads in a particular namespace, or choose specific workloads using a `workloadSelector`.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] See the Sidecar reference for more details.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] As well as helping you direct traffic around your mesh, Istio provides opt-in failure recovery and fault injection features that you can configure dynamically at runtime.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Using these features helps your applications operate reliably, ensuring that the service mesh can tolerate failing nodes and preventing localized failures from cascading to other nodes.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] A timeout is the amount of time that an Envoy proxy should wait for replies from a given service, ensuring that services don’t hang around waiting for replies indefinitely and that calls succeed or fail within a predictable timeframe.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] The Envoy timeout for HTTP requests is disabled in Istio by default.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] For some applications and services, Istio’s default timeout might not be appropriate.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] For example, a timeout that is too long could result in excessive latency from waiting for replies from failing services, while a timeout that is too short could result in calls failing unnecessarily while waiting for an operation involving multiple services to return.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] To find and use your optimal timeout settings, Istio lets you easily adjust timeouts dynamically on a per-service basis using virtual services without having to edit your service code.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] A retry setting specifies the maximum number of times an Envoy proxy attempts to connect to a service if the initial call fails.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Retries can enhance service availability and application performance by making sure that calls don’t fail permanently because of transient problems such as a temporarily overloaded service or network.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] The interval between retries (25ms+) is variable and determined automatically by Istio, preventing the called service from being overwhelmed with requests.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] The default retry behavior for HTTP requests is to retry twice before returning the error.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Like timeouts, Istio’s default retry behavior might not suit your application needs in terms of latency (too many retries to a failed service can slow things down) or availability.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Also like timeouts, you can adjust your retry settings on a per-service basis in virtual services without having to touch your service code.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You can also further refine your retry behavior by adding per-retry timeouts, specifying the amount of time you want to wait for each retry attempt to successfully connect to the service.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] The following example configures a maximum of 3 retries to connect to this service subset after an initial call failure, each with a 2 second timeout.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Circuit breakers are another useful mechanism Istio provides for creating resilient microservice-based applications.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] In a circuit breaker, you set limits for calls to individual hosts within a service, such as the number of concurrent connections or how many times calls to this host have failed.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Once that limit has been reached the circuit breaker “trips” and stops further connections to that host.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Using a circuit breaker pattern enables fast failure rather than clients trying to connect to an overloaded or failing host.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] As circuit breaking applies to “real” mesh destinations in a load balancing pool, you configure circuit breaker thresholds in destination rules, with the settings applying to each individual host in the service.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] You can find out more about creating circuit breakers in Circuit Breaking.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] After you’ve configured your network, including failure recovery policies, you can use Istio’s fault injection mechanisms to test the failure recovery capacity of your application as a whole.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Fault injection is a testing method that introduces errors into a system to ensure that it can withstand and recover from error conditions.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Using fault injection can be particularly useful to ensure that your failure recovery policies aren’t incompatible or too restrictive, potentially resulting in critical services being unavailable.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Unlike other mechanisms for introducing errors, such as delaying packets or killing pods at the network layer, Istio lets you inject faults at the application layer.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] This lets you inject more relevant failures, such as HTTP error codes, to get more relevant results.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] For example, this virtual service introduces a 5 second delay for 1 out of every 1000 requests to the `ratings` service.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] For detailed instructions on how to configure delays and aborts, see Fault Injection.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Istio failure recovery features are completely transparent to the application.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] Applications don’t know if an Envoy sidecar proxy is handling failures for a called service before returning a response.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] This means that if you are also setting failure recovery policies in your application code you need to keep in mind that both work independently, and therefore might conflict.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] For example, suppose you can have two timeouts, one configured in a virtual service and another in the application.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] The application sets a 2 second timeout for an API call to a service.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] However, you configured a 3 second timeout with 1 retry in your virtual service.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] In this case, the application’s timeout kicks in first, so your Envoy timeout and retry attempt has no effect.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] While Istio failure recovery features improve the reliability and availability of services in the mesh, applications must handle the failure or errors and take appropriate fallback actions.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] For example, when all instances in a load balancing pool have failed, Envoy returns an `HTTP 503` code.
[src:istio-mesh/traffic-management] The application must implement any fallback logic needed to handle the `HTTP 503` error code.
[src:istio-mesh/what-is-istio] Istio addresses the challenges developers and operators face with a distributed or microservices architecture.
[src:istio-mesh/what-is-istio] Whether you're building from scratch, migrating existing applications to cloud native, or securing your existing estate, Istio can help.
[src:istio-mesh/what-is-istio] A **service mesh** is an infrastructure layer that gives applications capabilities like zero-trust security, observability, and advanced traffic management, without code changes.
[src:istio-mesh/what-is-istio] **Istio** is the most popular, powerful, and trusted service mesh.
[src:istio-mesh/what-is-istio] Founded by Google, IBM and Lyft in 2016, Istio is a graduated project in the Cloud Native Computing Foundation alongside projects like Kubernetes and Prometheus.
[src:istio-mesh/what-is-istio] Istio ensures that cloud native and distributed systems are resilient, helping modern enterprises maintain their workloads across diverse platforms while staying connected and protected.
[src:istio-mesh/what-is-istio] It enables security and governance controls including mTLS encryption, policy management and access control, powers network features like canary deployments, A/B testing, load balancing, failure recovery, and adds observability of traffic across your estate.
[src:istio-mesh/what-is-istio] Istio is not confined to the boundaries of a single cluster, network or runtime — services running on Kubernetes or VMs, multi-cloud, hybrid, or on-premises, can be included within a single mesh.
[src:istio-mesh/what-is-istio] Extensible by design and supported by a broad ecosystem of contributors and partners, Istio offers packaged integrations and distributions for various use cases.
[src:istio-mesh/what-is-istio] You can install Istio independently or opt for managed support from commercial vendors providing Istio-based solutions.
[src:istio-mesh/what-is-istio] Istio provides a market-leading zero-trust solution based on workload identity, mutual TLS, and strong policy controls.
[src:istio-mesh/what-is-istio] Istio delivers the value of BeyondProd in open source, while avoiding vendor lock-in or SPOFs.
[src:istio-mesh/what-is-istio] Istio generates telemetry within the service mesh, enabling observability on service behavior.
[src:istio-mesh/what-is-istio] It integrates with APM systems including Grafana and Prometheus to deliver insightful metrics for operators to troubleshoot, maintain, and optimize applications.
[src:istio-mesh/what-is-istio] Istio simplifies traffic routing and service-level configuration, allowing easy control over flow between services and setup of tasks like A/B testing, canary deployments, and staged rollouts with percentage-based traffic splits.
[src:istio-mesh/what-is-istio] Istio offers two data plane modes for users to choose.
[src:istio-mesh/what-is-istio] Deploy with the new ambient mode for a simplified app operational lifecycle or with traditional sidecars for complex configurations.
[src:istio-mesh/what-is-istio] Built on the industry standard gateway proxy for cloud native applications, Istio is highly performative and extensible by design.
[src:istio-mesh/what-is-istio] Add custom traffic functionality with WebAssembly, or integrate third-party policy systems.
[src:istio-mesh/what-is-istio] Istio has been designed for modern workloads and engineered by a vast community of innovators across the cloud native landscape.
[src:istio-mesh/what-is-istio] Confidently deploy Istio across production workloads.
[src:istio-mesh/what-is-istio] All releases are fully accessible at no cost.
